f(x) &= \sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21} - \sqrt{-x^2 + 3x + 10} \\
&= \sqrt{(7 - x)(x + 3)} - \sqrt{(5 - x)(x + 2)}.
\end{align*}We want to minimize $f(x),$ so we want to minimize the difference between the two square roots.  The square roots are defined for $-3 \le x \le 5.$  Also, note that
\[f(-3) = \sqrt{10} - \sqrt{1} = \sqrt{10} - 1,\]\[f(5) = \sqrt{2} - \sqrt{7},\]and $f(x)$ is continuous on $[-3,5].$

