unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(sqrt((7 - x)*(x + 3)) - sqrt((5 - x)*(x + 2)));
}

draw(graph(func,-3,5));
draw((-3,0)--(5,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,2));

label("$f(x)$", (5,func(5)), E);
label("$f(-3)$", (-3,func(-3)), W);
[/asy]

Thus, by the Extreme Value Theorem, $f(x)$ attains a minimum value on $[-3,5].$

We can write
\begin{align*}
f(x) &= \sqrt{(7 - x)(x + 3)} - \sqrt{(5 - x)(x + 2)} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{(7 - x)(x + 3)}{x + 3}} - \sqrt{\frac{(5 - x)(x + 2)}{x + 2}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{(7 - x)(x + 3)}{x + 3}} - \sqrt{\frac{(5 - x)(x + 2)}{x + 2}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{7x + 21 - x^2 - 3x}{x + 3}} - \sqrt{\frac{5x + 10 - x^2 - 2x}{x + 2}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{-x^2 + 4x + 21}{x + 3}} - \sqrt{\frac{-x^2 + 3x + 10}{x + 2}}.
\end{align*}Since $x + 3$ and $x + 2$ are positive on $[-3,5],$ we can multiply both sides by $\sqrt{x + 3} \sqrt{x + 2}$ to get
\[\sqrt{x + 3} \sqrt{x + 2} f(x) = \sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21} \sqrt{x + 2} - \sqrt{-x^2 + 3x + 10} \sqrt{x + 3}.\]Now, we want to minimize $f(x),$ so we can try to minimize
\[\sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21} \sqrt{x + 2} - \sqrt{-x^2 + 3x + 10} \sqrt{x + 3}.\]Note that
\[\sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21} \sqrt{x + 2} - \sqrt{-x^2 + 3x + 10} \sqrt{x + 3} = 0\]when
\[\sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21} \sqrt{x + 2} = \sqrt{-x^2 + 3x + 10} \sqrt{x + 3}.\]Squaring both sides, we get
\[(-x^2 + 4x + 21)(x + 2) = (-x^2 + 3x + 10)(x + 3).\]This simplifies to $x = 1.$

We can check that $f(1) = \sqrt{24} - \sqrt{14} < f(-3)$ and $f(1) < f(5).$  Therefore, the minimum value of $f(x)$ is $\boxed{\sqrt{24} - \sqrt{14}}.$

